<p>X Extra Page.</p>
<p>I speak of course, of the men, who have no ties to keep them to the beaten track, who are physically fit to face the more strenuous life.  There are many who have to remain through force of circumstance and general unfitness and to them the inaction is a continual drag.  They sit and listen to the talk of war with feelings of their own impotence, straining at the leash like hounds thirsting for the chase.  They are debarred from doing their share in the fighting and   <strike>they feel it in their act</strike> they show their feelings in their every action, every word.</p>
